ce:section.ce:para:
To confirm the chemical constitution and interactions between N-GQDs and polymer matrix, FT-IR and XPS measurements were performed. All the membranes displayed the adsorption peaks at 1900 cm−1 (CO), 1643 cm−1 (NCO), and 690 cm−1 (NH) from the common PA layers [29,37] (Fig. 3a). With the incorporation of N-GQDs, the intensity of peak at 1776 cm−1 deriving from CO tensile vibration of carbonyl in carboxyl groups and ester groups increased. It might demonstrate that the amino group in N-GQDs could compete with the reaction sites of the acyl chloride group in TMC with PIP, causing the hydrolysis of the unreacted acyl chloride group to form more carboxyl groups. Besides, it might be attributed to the esterification reaction between the hydroxyl group in N-GQDs and the acyl chloride group in TMC, indicating the manipulation of N-GQDs on the networks of the PA layer (Fig. S5,6). Furthermore, XPS measurement was conducted to interpret the effect of N-GQDs incorporation on the networks and cross-linking degree of PA layer. Consistent with the result of the EDS analysis (Fig. S7), the XPS spectrum of the N-GQDs+DA/PA layer showed a higher intensity of N1s (at 400.0 eV) and a lower intensity of O1s (at 532.0 eV) (Fig. 3b). On closer observation of the deconvolution of C1s, N1s, O1s core level (Fig. 4
                        , Table 1
                        ), after incorporation of N-GQDs into the PA layer, the CO proportion at 288.0 eV from the high resolution of C1s spectrum increased from 13.21% to 13.59%, while CN proportion at 286.0 eV decreased from 40.10% to 34.64%. Additionally, for the high resolution of O1s spectrum, the OCO proportion mainly deriving from the hydrolysis of unreacted OCCl groups in TMC [38] increased from 30.38% to 33.32%, while OCN proportion in amide groups decreased from 69.62% to 47.58%, thus elevating the CO/CN ratio. It concluded that N-GQDs incorporation could contribute to the reduction in the cross-linking degree of PA layer and the formation of a relatively loose network. This structure would be conducive to improving water permeation of the TFN membranes in concentrated seawater separation.
